			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/investment-banking/">Investment Banking</a> | <a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/other-topics/wall-street-earnings/">Wall Street Earnings</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Wary Goldman Reduces Pay Ratio, Even as Profit Rises</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Rachel Abrams			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-01-16T12:58:01+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">January 16, 2014 7:58 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">January 16, 2014 7:58 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/17/business/Goldman/Goldman-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/17/business/Goldman/Goldman-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/17/business/Goldman/Goldman-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002655479" width="592" height="402" alt="Lloyd C. Blankfein of Goldman Sachs, which had an 8 percent rise in profit but a drop in net revenue in a major unit."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="402"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Lloyd C. Blankfein of Goldman Sachs, which had an 8 percent rise in profit but a drop in net revenue in a major unit.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Rebecca Cook/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/01/16/goldman-profit-declines-19-percent/" data-title="Wary Goldman Reduces Pay Ratio, Even as Profit Rises" data-description="While the bank reported an 8 percent increase in annual profit, to $8.04 billion, it tightened its belt as net revenue in its fixed-income, currency and commodities unit dropped sharply. . ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="t19h45m" class="update">Updated, 7:45 p.m. | </span>Faced with continuing declines in one of its core businesses and an uncertain regulatory environment, <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=GS&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Goldman Sachs Group Inc">Goldman Sachs</a> is keeping a close eye on what it pays its employees.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In announcing its fourth-quarter and full-year results on Thursday, Goldman said it cut its compensation ratio to the lowest level in four years. It set aside $12.61 billion for pay in 2013, or 36.9 percent of net revenue, down from $12.94 billion, or 37.9 percent, in 2012.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âGoldman is showing a discipline on compensation that no other bank is showing,â said Brad Hintz, an analyst with Sanford Bernstein.</p>
<div class="entry entry-related"><h4>Related Links</h4>	<div class="entry-related">
		<ul>
					<li><a href="//www.goldmansachs.com/media-relations/press-releases/current/pdfs/2013-q4-results.pdf" title="Goldman Sachs earnings release"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/multimedia/icons/document_icon.gif" alt="Documents" width="10" height="12" border="0"> Document: Goldman Sachs earnings release (PDF)</a></li>
				</ul>
	</div>
	</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While Goldman reported an 8 percent increase in annual profit, to $8.04 billion, the highest level in three years, the bank has tightened its belt as net revenue in its fixed-income, currency and commodities unit has dropped sharply. Net revenue in that division dropped 15 percent in the fourth quarter, to $1.72 billion, and 13 percent, to $8.65 billion, for 2013.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That weakness contributed to a 19 percent decline in fourth-quarter profit, though strength in equity underwriting helped the bank beat Wall Street estimates. Net income was $2.33 billion, or $4.60 a share, compared with $2.89 billion, or $5.60 a share, in the period a year earlier. Analysts had expected earnings of $4.22 a share, according to data from <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=TRI&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Thomson Reuters Corporation">Thomson Reuters</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âOur work in advancing our client franchise and in ensuring continued cost discipline has allowed us to provide solid returns even in a somewhat challenging environment,â <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/b/lloyd_c_blankfein/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Lloyd C. Blankfein.">Lloyd C. Blankfein</a>, Goldmanâs chairman and chief executive, said in a statement. âWe believe that we are well positioned to generate solid returns as the economy continues to heal and provide considerable upside for our shareholders as conditions materially improve.â</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/17/business/dbpix-goldman-schwartz/dbpix-goldman-schwartz-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/17/business/dbpix-goldman-schwartz/dbpix-goldman-schwartz-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/17/business/dbpix-goldman-schwartz/dbpix-goldman-schwartz-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002654113" width="190" height="266" alt="Harvey Schwartz, Goldmanâs chief financial officer."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="266"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Harvey Schwartz, Goldmanâs chief financial officer.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Goldman Sachs, via Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bank has not been shy about its focus on cost-saving and efficiency. But Harvey M. Schwartz, Goldmanâs chief financial officer, stopped short of telling analysts on a conference call that lower compensation ratios would be the bankâs new reality in the future.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âHe demurred on that,â Mr. Hintz said. âTelling the employees that the comp ratio is permanently down is a bit demoralizing.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Based on 2013 compensation figures, Goldman set aside an average of about $383,300 for each of its 32,900 employees, down from an average of $399,500 for its 32,400 employees in 2012.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Employees may be cheered by the bankâs return on equity, which rose to 11 percent in 2013 from 10.7 percent in 2012. That helped drive Goldmanâs stock price up more than 20 percent in 2013 â good news for employees who received deferred compensation in previous years.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIn the end, yes, your compensation is going down, but your stock is going to be healthier,â Mr. Hintz said. Shares of Goldman fell 2 percent on Thursday, or $3.58, to close at $175.17.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Goldman has lifted returns above its generally accepted cost of capital, about 10 percent. Unlike other large banks, Goldman has not publicly disclosed a return-on-equity target.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWhen we put out an R.O.E. target, I think first and foremost, we want it to be credible and we want it to be achievable,â Mr. Schwartz said on the call. âWhen you hear from us, thatâs what it will be.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Over all, Goldman generated net revenue of $8.78 billion in the fourth quarter, beating average expectations of $7.7 billion. Net revenue for 2013 reached $34.21 billion, nearly flat with $34.16 billion in 2012.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Unlike commercial banks, Goldman depends on revenue from its trading and investment banking units, the latter of which fared well in the fourth quarter. Improving market conditions helped to more than double equity underwriting revenue, to $622 million, while overall net underwriting revenue reached $1.13 billion, a 26 percent gain from the period a year earlier.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bank is also trying to figure out how its bottom line will be affected by the recently adopted <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/subjects/v/volcker_rule/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the Volcker Rule.">Volcker Rule</a>, which is intended to deter banks from making risky bets with their own money, and other government regulations. Goldman has formed a Volcker Rule unit â a team of fewer than 10 people â to prepare the firm as the new rule takes effect.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Volcker Rule prohibits banks from owning more than 3 percent of a <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/private-equity/?inline=nyt-classifier" class="tickerized" title="More articles about private equity.">private equity</a> or hedge fund and severely restricts proprietary trading. But on the call with analysts, Mr. Schwartz did not seem concerned about Goldmanâs ability to mitigate its risk.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe donât see anything in the rule that prevents us from continuing to hedge,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Goldman is not pulling back from its fixed-income operations like some other firms, which are choosing to focus on areas like wealth management. Goldman said it had no plans to slow activities in its fixed-income unit. And Mr. Schwartz told analysts that he expected Goldman to benefit from other firmsâ pullback.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Goldman said it was also not overly concerned about increased competition for new recruits from industries like technology and alternative asset management. While cuts in compensation may not seem like the greatest advertisement, Goldman executives say they have not seen a decline in applicants in recent years. The firm recently received 97,000 applications to its analyst and trading program. Of those, it accepted just less than 3 percent. Goldman also received 17,000 applications for slightly more than 300 jobs in its investment banking division.</p>
